,"1354–Female":"1354–Afdød","1462":"1462","1373":"1373","1384":"1384","1351":"1351","1 April 1401":"1. april 1401","1382":"1382","1390":"1390","1401":"1401","1433":"1433","1410":"1410","1377":"1377","1354":"1354","about 1372":"omkring 1372","Baconsthorpe, Norfolk, England":"Baconsthorpe, Norfolk, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England"},"nl":{"1373–1433":"1373–1433","1377–1410":"1377–1410","1401–1462":"1401–1462","1351–1384":"1351–1384","1354–Female":"1354–Overleden","1462":"1462","1373":"1373","1384":"1384","1351":"1351","1 April 1401":"1 april 1401","1382":"1382","1390":"1390","1401":"1401","1433":"1433","1410":"1410","1377":"1377","1354":"1354","about 1372":"circa 1372","Baconsthorpe, Norfolk, England":"Baconsthorpe, Norfolk, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England"},"en":{"1373–1433":"1373–1433","1377–1410":"1377–1410","1401–1462":"1401–1462","1351–1384":"1351–1384","1354–Female":"1354–Deceased","1462":"1462","1373":"1373","1384":"1384","1351":"1351","1 April 1401":"1 April 1401","1382":"1382","1390":"1390","1401":"1401","1433":"1433","1410":"1410","1377":"1377","1354":"1354","about 1372":"about 1372","Baconsthorpe, Norfolk, England":"Baconsthorpe, Norfolk, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bacon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin) and French: from the Norman French personal name <i>Bacun</i>, derived from the ancient Germanic name <i>Bac(c)o</i>, <i>Bahho</i>, based on the element <i>bag</i> ‘(to) fight, (to) dispute’. The name was relatively common among the Normans in the form <i>Bacus</i>, of which the oblique case was <i>Bacon</i>.","English and French: from Middle English, Old French <i>bacun</i>, <i>bacon</i> ‘bacon’ (a word of ancient Germanic origin, akin to   Back   3), probably a metonymic occupational name for a preparer and seller of cured pork.","History: Gilles Bacon from Normandy, France, is documented in Quebec City, QC, in 1647. — Michael Bacon from England arrived in Dedham, MA, in 1640. Nathanial Bacon, from Stratton, Cornwall, arrived in Barnstaple, MA, in 1639. Another Nathaniel Bacon (1647–76), from Friston Hall, Suffolk, emigrated to VA and settled at Curl's Neck on the James river."],"variants":[{"name":"Bagg","meanings":["English:","from Middle English <i>bagge</i> ‘bag, pack, bundle’, hence a metonymic occupational name for a maker of bags and sacks of various kinds, including wallets and purses. It might also have been used for a beggar, or for one who carried their belongings in a bag.","from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Bago</i> (<i>Bac(c)o</i>, <i>Bahho</i>), from the root <i>bag-</i> ‘to fight’ (see   Bacon   2)."]},{"name":"Back","meanings":["English (Devon, Kent, Sussex, and Norfolk): from the Middle English personal name <i>Bakke</i> (Old English <i>Bacca</i>). It is of uncertain origin, but may have been a byname in the same sense as 3.","English: nickname from Middle English <i>bakke</i> ‘bat’, of uncertain application, perhaps a nickname for a person with poor eyesight, from the expression ‘blind as a bat’.","English: from Middle English <i>bakke</i> ‘back’ (Old English <i>bæc</i>), hence a nickname for someone with a hunched back or some other noticeable peculiarity of the back or spine, or a topographic name for someone who lived on a hill or ridge, or at the rear of a settlement."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":9,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When John Bacon was born in 1373, in Baconsthorpe, Norfolk, England, his father, Roger Bacon, was 23 and his mother, Catherine, was 20. He married Maud de Bedingfield in 1390, in Baconsthorpe, Norfolk, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1433, in his hometown, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1373–1433":"1373–1433","1377–1410":"1377–1410","1401–1462":"1401–1462","1351–1384":"1351–1384","1354–Female":"1354–Surnud","1462":"1462","1373":"1373","1384":"1384","1351":"1351","1 April 1401":"1. aprill 1401","1382":"1382","1390":"1390","1401":"1401","1433":"1433","1410":"1410","1377":"1377","1354":"1354","about 1372":"umbes 1372","Baconsthorpe, Norfolk, England":"Baconsthorpe, Norfolk, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England"},"fi":{"1373–1433":"1373–1433","1377–1410":"1377–1410","1401–1462":"1401–1462","1351–1384":"1351–1384","1354–Female":"1354–Kuollut","1462":"1462","1373":"1373","1384":"1384","1351":"1351","1 April 1401":"1. huhtikuuta 1401","1382":"1382","1390":"1390","1401":"1401","1433":"1433","1410":"1410","1377":"1377","1354":"1354","about 1372":"noin 1372","Baconsthorpe, Norfolk, England":"Baconsthorpe, Norfolk, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England"},"fr":{"1373–1433":"1373–1433","1377–1410":"1377–1410","1401–1462":"1401–1462","1351–1384":"1351–1384","1354–Female":"1354–Décédée","1462":"1462","1373":"1373","1384":"1384","1351":"1351","1 April 1401":"1 avril 1401","1382":"1382","1390":"1390","1401":"1401","1433":"1433","1410":"1410","1377":"1377","1354":"1354","about 1372":"environ 1372","Baconsthorpe, Norfolk, England":"Baconsthorpe, Norfolk, Angleterre","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque John Bacon est né en 1373, à Baconsthorpe, Norfolk, Angleterre, son père, Roger Bacon, avait 23 ans et sa mère, Catherine, avait 20 ans. Il a épousé Maud de Bedingfield en 1390, à Baconsthorpe, Norfolk, Angleterre. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils. Il 